  "summary": "Inspector Taverner interrogates Philip Leonidis regarding his father’s will and the family's internal dynamics. Philip explains that Aristide created a new will in 1945, which left £100,000 to his stepmother, Brenda, and divided the remaining estate into three equal parts for Philip, his brother Roger, and Roger's three grandchildren. Philip denies having a financial motive for the death, noting that Aristide provided for both him and his wife, Margarita. Regarding his father's marriage, Philip describes the union as happy but admits he considered it unwise. He also clarifies that Lawrence Brown serves as a private tutor for Philip and Josephine's children and resides on the other side of the house due to available space. Philip denies any knowledge of an intimate relationship between Brown and Brenda.\n\nTaverner then interviews Margarita Leonidis, a former actress. Margarita claims that at the time of Aristide's death, she was in London attending a fashion show and having drinks. She states that she loved her husband and notes that she and Brenda do not see each other often because they have little in common. When Taverner questions her about a potential romantic involvement between Brenda and Lawrence Brown, Margarita defends Brenda's character. She asserts she has seen no signs of such a relationship and maintains that she only recognizes Brenda as her husband's wife. Following the interview, the Inspector moves to discuss the household servants.",
